think. Not sure about this. And then you. I'm not

14:10.588 --> 14:12.090
sure whether you came before. Was Claude here when 
you came? Or after? I got here in the fall of 1969,

14:15.088 --> 14:25.843
but taught in the architecture department for one 
year until a space was made on the faculty for me.

14:26.704 --> 14:33.073
There was no position authorized at that time, as I 
understood it. OK. Yeah, I guess that was it,

14:33.093 --> 14:36.157
wasn't it? Yeah. I remember I drove you free of 
charge back from San Francisco to College

14:36.297 --> 14:41.685
Station. only to benefit by my superb company. I 
know. Wonderful. That was it. But that was also a

14:47.701 --> 15:04.419
gathering of the clans, too, because Jim Gardner, 
Jesus Hinojosa, myself, and Bob Cornish all

14:47.701 --> 15:04.419
worked together in an outfit called Will Z. 
Hammond Blair in the Bay Area of San Francisco. And

15:05.681 --> 15:08.584
this constituted the primary faculty and who were 
largely hired, they may not believe this, but they

15:09.256 --> 15:22.371
were largely hired for their strengths and 
divergent points of view on the planning process.

15:22.891 --> 15:27.598
The only thing we held in common was that it should 
be at least comprehensive. But we soon depart

15:28.119 --> 15:32.105
company after that. And frankly, it was with the 
students in mind that diversity was brought on

15:32.265 --> 15:39.155
board. We felt that in my architecture training, I 
never had enough diversity. And I wasn't going to

15:44.323 --> 15:47.307
repeat that mistake in the planning program. But 
now we've all come to know which point of view is

15:48.349 --> 15:50.693
correct. It is correct. Of course, mine. That's 
how that started. And I knew these divergent point

15:56.421 --> 16:06.658
of views, having worked with these gentlemen, and 
that was exactly why that was the main thrust in

15:56.421 --> 16:06.658
hiring. In those days, there was no affirmative 
action or nothing. You just went out and got the

16:09.162 --> 16:11.506
people that agreed to work with you. And if they 
did, they were on board. And the program enjoyed an

16:15.352 --> 16:20.320
awful lot of dynamics and flexibility in that 
regard in its beginning. Another thing was that I

16:21.599 --> 16:40.030
don't think we saw the planning program here as 
one, another common thing we shared was that it

16:21.599 --> 16:40.030
must be comprehensive and it need not necessarily 
specialize in any given area of the planning

16:21.599 --> 16:40.030
process. Those were options that an individual 
student could do, but that was not necessarily

16:40.212 --> 16:47.483
going to be the general thrust of the program. It 
was not going to be transportation engineering or

16:47.503 --> 16:51.809
hospital planning or anything of the sort. It was 
general planning in its broadest meaning and

16:52.050 --> 16:57.618
interdisciplinary in its nature. And

16:59.281 --> 17:08.194
I guess also implicitly and explicitly by some of 
the faculty, we really thought we would have more

17:08.765 --> 17:13.709
influence than history proved that we had on the 
rest of the programs. We summed up one of the early

17:13.889 --> 17:23.618
graduates, Larry Priesmeier, who was a recent 
graduate in the architecture program and was

17:13.889 --> 17:23.618
recruited into the planning program. And in one 
conference in the recruitment process where he

17:24.418 --> 17:38.350
was hesitant to join, he said, well, will I have to 
give up architecture when I get my master's degree

17:24.418 --> 17:38.350
in planning? And what I said to him then, and I still 
believe in now, and I wish we were more effective in

17:39.106 --> 17:52.483
this, was I said, no, Larry, you'll just practice 
architecture differently as a result of having a

17:39.106 --> 17:52.483
plan to do it. And I had high hopes that our program 
would do that. It would influence the programs in

17:56.669 --> 18:03.257
engineering and architecture and landscape 
architecture to cope with the broader social,

18:03.625 --> 18:10.554
political, and economic factors that work in 
their work and make them more aware of the

18:03.625 --> 18:10.554
implications toward design. I'm not so sure a 
program was all that successful in that regard. It

18:14.999 --> 18:19.805
was a goal that was never really attained in my 
book. The planning faculty has attempted to work

18:19.825 --> 18:33.362
with the environmental design department, as 
you're painfully aware, particularly with the

18:19.825 --> 18:33.362
undergraduate programs, but also with other 
departments for graduate courses. in achieving

18:33.865 --> 19:00.362
this and it's been an uphill struggle for various 
reasons i think most of which have to do with the

18:33.865 --> 19:00.362
politics of the college yeah and i also laid at the 
doorstep of having graduated from harvard who

18:33.865 --> 19:00.362
ostensibly was in the same boat of 
interdisciplinary sharing and working with one

18:33.865 --> 19:00.362
another a la gropius methods and techniques It 
wasn't a practice anymore there, frankly, at the

19:00.342 --> 19:05.788
wellspring of all this thing that has been at Texas 
A&M. And I really think that the behavior that we

19:06.389 --> 19:15.999
expect out of our students in this 
interdisciplinary activity isn't modeled by the

19:06.389 --> 19:15.999
faculty. The faculty won't act 
interdisciplinary. So how can we expect students

19:20.824 --> 19:26.991
to see the benefit of that if the faculties won't 
even do it? Unilateral efforts have been made.

19:30.404 --> 19:38.633
Jose and I worked together for Henry Cisneros, the 
mayor of San Antonio, one of our graduates in

19:30.404 --> 19:38.633
planning, you see. Now on the Board of Regents. Now 
on the Board of Regents of Texas A&M. He and I,

19:44.280 --> 19:56.995
having separate classes, his in planning and mine 
in fourth-year design and environmental design,

19:44.280 --> 19:56.995
unilaterally worked out a common block of time 
where our students could work together. When that

19:58.477 --> 20:11.777
contract was renewed for the second semester, 
administrative blocks were thrown in the way of us

19:58.477 --> 20:11.777
duplicating that effort.

20:12.398 --> 20:13.439
When did that happen? Well, that happened last 
year. Yeah. And so there doesn't seem to be a

20:17.645 --> 20:23.834
predisposition to interdisciplinary... But 
that wasn't done by the planning department. Oh,

20:25.916 --> 20:26.517
no, no, no. The planning department was not at 
fault here. It was my own department head who is no

20:28.780 --> 20:33.407
longer a department head. He could not see his way 
clear to schedule my hours in such a way that they

20:33.427 --> 20:40.036
would match Chewy's. And so... Our students 
didn't participate in that rather successful

20:42.790 --> 20:50.056
project that Chewy did for the San Antonio area. 
But this is the thing. See, this is the thing. It's

20:54.060 --> 20:57.723
always kind of held back. The often used excuse 
that somehow the monies can't be allocated

20:57.743 --> 21:11.835
administratively to professors having joint 
appointments and that sort of thing is also just, I

20:57.743 --> 21:11.835
think, shibboleths and nonsense.

21:12.288 --> 21:15.631
There isn't the commitment to our rhetoric here. 
Makes a nice story, but really, the commitment's

21:17.894 --> 21:21.257
lacking. The will to work interdisciplinary 
isn't here, either, among a good many of the

21:21.277 --> 21:27.243
faculty. They want to do their own thing. Of 
course, if this continues for any length of time,

21:29.966 --> 21:33.830
it leads to a general malaise.

21:36.473 --> 21:41.738
Yeah, well, it'll lead to the individual there 
will be other programs throughout the United

21:42.511 --> 21:53.424
States that really take advantage of the strength 
that's to be gained from interdisciplinary

21:42.511 --> 21:53.424
behavior and interdisciplinary work. And we'll 
wonder why our programs are not as attractive as

21:53.444 --> 22:00.272
they used to be. Well, for example, there are joint 
degree programs that have blossomed in a few of the

22:00.292 --> 22:07.982
more heads-up institutions. You mentioned 
Harvard, and Harvard has a joint degree program

22:08.823 --> 22:12.467
with law and planning, and so does Berkeley. 
Right, right. And I went to a joint program. I did. I

22:18.555 --> 22:20.318
took all my economics at MIT. And they had a working 
relationship with a school down the road a piece.

22:26.649 --> 22:30.536
And you took whatever courses you wanted over at 
MIT. And then they, in turn, granted you the degree

22:30.636 --> 22:37.628
from one of the two schools, whichever you were 
resident in.

22:39.447 --> 22:41.550
Yeah, so I was used to the interdisciplinary 
thing. I was used to the thing. I come to it very

22:44.594 --> 22:47.197
naturally, and I thought it was natural for people 
to do this. The complexity of today's world almost

22:47.538 --> 22:54.187
demands that you have these kinds of approaches. 
But not yet, and not here.

23:00.956 --> 23:01.877
Yeah, I think... You know, in those time-honored 
questions they ask you when you're on your 100th

23:02.887 --> 23:10.042
birthday, would you do it all differently? And my 
answer to that is, no, I wouldn't do it any

23:10.062 --> 23:13.509
differently. All I wanted to ever do, you know, and 
what I did was make a difference. You know, the old

23:18.179 --> 23:22.127
time-honored Greek notion about that Athens was 
better for you having lived there. And I feel that

23:25.882 --> 23:38.818
with regard to our faculty and this program, that 
the state of Texas in planning and this university

23:25.882 --> 23:38.818
has been a little bit better for us having had this 
program here. And I have absolutely no regrets,

23:39.439 --> 23:50.072
implied or otherwise, about the serious and 
meaningful contributions this program has made

23:39.439 --> 23:50.072
as it's evolved over the years. And none of its 
graduates should, in my estimation, have any

23:50.812 --> 24:02.168
regrets regarding what they got here and what 
they've since done since they've left here. It has

24:02.189 --> 24:06.575
produced some stellar people doing very 
effective jobs. And we can all be proud of that.

